@Kenny

Also not a musician, but know a little Italian, and it seems to me that the simplest way of saying "slower" is "Più lentamente" or "Più lento."  It seems I've seen the latter in a musical context, but maybe I'm mistaken; as I said, I'm not a musician.

Since you are one, can you weigh in on whether these terms are indeed used, and if they are more or less common than MENO MOSSO?

@Steve L
Yes, "più lento" is the simplest and most generic way of saying "slower". If the composer specifies "meno mosso", there is added an idea of "calm it down" or "less agitated" (which could also be "più tranquillo" or "meno agitato"). If the composer says "ritardando" or "accelerando" there is implied a (more or less gradual) process of 
slowing down or speeding up. There are more variations, like "rallentando" which is substantially the same as "ritardando". (I've been a professional musician in Italy for over half a century.)

@SP
